  "topic": "File System Internals and Links",
  "slides": [
    {
      "slideId": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Understanding File System Internals"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "Linux file systems store files using inodes, which contain metadata like ownership, permissions, size, and location on disk."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Every file has an inode number. The inode does not store the file name—names belong to directory entries. This is why multiple names can point to the same data."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Term", "Meaning"],
            ["Inode", "Data structure storing file info (metadata, disk location)"],
            ["Metadata", "Information like size, owner, permissions, timestamps"],
            ["Directory Entry", "Maps file names to inode numbers"],
            ["Data Blocks", "Where actual file content is stored"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "inode = identity of a file. Name = just a label pointing to that identity."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Checking Inodes & Metadata"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "We can view a file's inode number and metadata using ls and stat commands."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "ls -i file.txt",
          "description": "Shows the inode number of the file."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "stat file.txt",
          "description": "Displays detailed metadata of a file."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Metadata Field", "Description"],
            ["Size", "File size in bytes"],
            ["Access/Modify Time", "When file was opened or changed"],
            ["UID/GID", "File owner and group owner"],
            ["Permissions", "rw-r--r-- style access control settings"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Two files can look different but share the same inode → hard link."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },
    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Hard Links vs Soft (Symbolic) Links"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Links are alternate ways to access a file. Hard links share the same inode; symbolic links point to the filename."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Type", "Points To", "Breaks If Original Deleted?", "Cross Filesystem?"],
            ["Hard Link", "Inode / actual data", "❌ No", "❌ No"],
            ["Symbolic Link (symlink)", "Original file name path", "✔️ Yes", "✔️ Yes"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "ln file.txt hardlink.txt",
          "description": "Creates a hard link (same inode, same data)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "ln -s file.txt symlink.txt",
          "description": "Creates a symbolic link (shortcut-like pointer)."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Hard link = clone of file reference. Symlink = shortcut to file."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
